<dl id="s17019ci"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="us17" href="#s17019ci">Ithaca: </a><a href="../../ff/unbs/s17all.htm#s17019ci">sector 19(ci)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> abs. zero = -273C <small>Red</small></blockquote> <dd class="well"> <ul class="list-inline" id="s17019ci"><li>Ulysses </li><li><a href="../../ulex/s/lexs.htm#s17019ci">2021</a> </li><li><a href="../../ulex/s/s86.htm#s17019ci">2017</a> </li><li><a href="../../ulex/s/s86.htm#s17019ci">1986 (17.1247)</a> </li><li><a href="../../ulex/s/l22s.htm#s17019ci">1922</a> </li><li><ms href="#s17019ci">MS TS-B</ms> </li><li>JJA 16:119 </li><li><a name="sd3" href="../udra/u17da.htm#sd3">Usage</a> </li><li><a href="../../ulex/s/sd3.htm#s17019ci">Draft: 17.3</a></li> </ul> <blockquote class="sources"><mark>This temperature of -273&deg; C.</mark> is, however, one of great theoretical importance in the study of gases. It <maek>is called the <mark>absolute zero</mark> of temperature; and temperatures, reckoned from this point as the zero point, are called absolute temperatures. Any reading on the Centigrade scale is reduced to the equivalent reading on the absolute scale by adding 273. <small> Wentworth and Hill, <a name="TBOP" href="/udra/udex.htm#tbop"><cite title="source">A Text-Book of Physics</cite></a> (1904), 103</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
